text: hi everyone anthony fantano here
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new self-titled
record from edward sharp and the
magnetic zeros these guys are a
california indie rock and any folk band
who in my opinion have had one of the
more shocking falls from grace since
their debut full-length album release in
2009. and and when i say
shocking i mean sort of more in in
recent memory back in 2009 when they put
out their first full length up from
below it was an album that did not
necessarily turn a ton of heads upon its
initial release but it had a few nice
sleeper hits on it that got people into
the band sort of after the fact songs
like home really fantastic hit off of
this lp a song that is catchy very
joyful just jubilant instrumentation
that is a mix of folk and rock sounds
and the band's really huge
instrumental lineup showed with just how
gargantuan and monstrous their sound was
it was like listening to some kind of
giant folky arcade fire and when i think
about that theory or the idea of that in
my head i i'm into that but i don't
think edward sharp and the magnetic
zeros really carried forward into their
later releases to to really kind of
capitalize on that potential really
reach their full potential actually up
from below was far from a perfect album
but listening to the band's next full
length here was like
watching a director try to put out the
sequel to what essentially was a cult
film with
no budget and half of the original cast
everything sounded really rickety on
this album from the instrumentation to
the performances there just were not a
lot of good takes on this lp and i would
say the songwriting was just not as
concise
or succinct or just really
straightforward and memorable i just
think it's odd that edward sharp and the
magnetic zeros would give up their pop
appeal so easily especially considering
that their pop appeal was the best thing
they had going for them on up from below
because when it came to the worlds of
indie folk and indie pop they certainly
weren't trail blazing or creating any
new sounds or anything like that now
with this new self-titled full length of
theirs
edward sharp's pop appeal is still out
to lunch except this time i feel like
the band is is emphasizing that indie
folk vibe a little bit less and instead
they're they're going for something that
feels way
more vintage with some extremely tacked
on soul and previously edward sharp's
music has tipped its hat to the
psychedelic 60s but this time around on
this lp we're getting acid soaked guitar
solos really thumpy paul mccartney-esque
bass lines and drums that have a really
kind of hollow atmospheric thud to them
as if they were being recorded decades
upon decades ago instead of sounding
authentically vintage i think this
self-titled lp sounds more
messy and thrown together than here case
in point the song in the lion quite
possibly the worst mix song you'll hear
this year the horns the lead vocals the
horribly performed falsetto background
vocals and the drums all just completely
out of whack and some of these problems
aren't even specific to this track
consistently i would say the worst thing
about this album is ed sharpe's voice
while his singing was good and and
pretty tolerable on previous lps
i would say much of the time on this
album when ed sharp isn't really
screaming to reach notes that he doesn't
really have he's using this really
forced vibrato that that gets annoying
after a while as i'm listening to this
album
even though ed sharpe and the magnetic
zeros may have some real passion
for
the folk rock and the pop and the rock
of the 60s on this album i feel like
them trying to recreate it here is is
the equivalent to just watching a
broadway rendition of the 60s the
musical 60s versus some bad street
performance of it i would say that this
record is is essentially indie folks
answer to a prairie home companion which
is
incredibly dorky and incredibly hokey
show on npr
that dabbles in country folk music a
little bit of bluegrass as well but the
thing with the prairie home companion is
that it's kind of self-aware
tongue-in-cheek a lot of the time and i
don't really feel that vibe from edward
sharp and the magnetic zeros even though
ed sharp can get silly at times on this
album like on the song let's get high
when he's singing
ain't we all just japanese when we're
high i still can't help but feel like
this album is is a little serious at
points like this i mean if this song was
put out in 1963
at best today it would be like a novelty
song but now it just sounds ridiculous
then there's all these references to
love needing someone's love giving your
love we all have love for one another
again trying to recapture this emotional
philosophical sort of social sentiment
of young people from this era of music
that edward sharp and magnetic zeros are
trying to recreate on this record and
this is just one more thing on this
album that falls horribly short of
sounding like something i can take
seriously or really kind of believe in i
have to be completely honest and say
that this album
there isn't much about it i can say that
i liked i mean the production was
really
bad and you know just technically weak
the instrumentation again sounded really
flat and just
bodyless a lot of the time
just for some kind of cheap attempt to
recreate some dead sonic palette really
there were only flashes on this album
that that appealed to me like oh this
melody here sounds pretty good or this
vocal take sounds okay or i like this
guitar part here the only emotion that
this album really stirred up in me is
that it made me want to go listen to
frank zappa and the mothers were only in
it for the money i think after listening
to this album
maybe i came at least
a little close to gaining a quarter of
the anger or annoyance that frank zappa
had for hippies and their social circle
when he wrote this lp i'm essentially
feeling a light to decent three on this
thing if you've given it a listen what
did you think of it did you love it did
you hate it why what do you think i
should review next and that's it this
review is my opinion if you don't like
it here's a straw i want to give a shout
out to you you're the best only the
strong subscribe all mistakes were
intentional anthony fantano ed sharp
forever
